To create a Discord bot that responds to slash commands with the functionality to ban someone, you'll need to have Node.js installed on your computer. Use the following steps:


1. First, set up your project structure. Create a new directory and initialize a Node.js project within it:


   ```bash

   mkdir discord_ban_bot

   cd discord_ban_bot

   npm init -y

   ```


2. Install the necessary Discord.js library and the discord.js-commando package for handling slash commands:


   ```bash

   npm install discord.js

   npm install discord.js-commando

   ```


3. Now, create a new file named `index.js` and add the following code to set up the bot and add the 'ban' command:


   ```javascript

   const { Client, GatewayBot } = require('discord.js-commando');


   class MyBot extends GatewayBot {

       constructor(...options) {

           super(...options)


           this.on('ready', () => {

               console.log(`Logged in as ${this.user.tag}!`);

           });

       }


       onDidInstallCommands() {

           this.addCommands(['Ban', 'ban']);

       }

   }


   (() => {

       const bot = new MyBot('DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN');

       bot.start();

   })();

   ```


   Replace "DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN" with your actual bot token obtained from the Discord developer portal.


4. Run your bot with:


   ```bash

   node index.js

   ```


   Your bot should now be running, and you can add the 'ban' command by sending a request to Discord's Developer Portal and using the slash command slash.guildAddRole on a guild (server) in the app info section. The permission to send a message and manage messages needs to be assigned to the bot as well.

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& md) {
    std::string html;
    html += "<p>";

    for (int i = 0; i < md.length(); ++i) {
        char ch = md[i];

        if (ch == '#') { // Heading
            int size = 1;
            while (i + 1 < md.length() && md[i + 1] == '#') {
                i++;
                size++;
            }
            int dashes = size * 2 - 1;
            html += "<h" + std::to_string(size) + ">" + std::string(md.substr(i + 1, dashes)) + "</h" + std::to_string(size) + ">\n";
            i += dashes;
        } else if (ch == '*' || ch == '_') { // Emphasis
            int size = 1;
            while (i + 1 < md.length() && md[i + 1] == ch) {
                i++;
                size++;
            }
            int text = md.substr(i + 1, size - 1);
            html += "<em>" + text + "</em>\n";
            i += size;
        } else if (ch == '`' && md[i + 1] == '`') { // Code block
            int start = i + 2;
            int end = md.find('`', start) - 1;
            html += "<pre><code>" + md.substr(start, end - start + 1) + "</code></pre>\n";
            i = end + 1;
        }
    }

    html += "</p>";
    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "## Heading 1\n*Emphasized* text\n`Code block`\n## Heading 2\n_More emphasized_ text";
    std::string html = markdown_to_html(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

Creating a smooth and visually appealing snake game in C with animations would typically involve several steps and considerations. However, due to C's limitations in handling graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and animations directly, you often need to integrate with a graphics library or use a framework that allows for low-level graphics rendering.

Here's a broad step-by-step guide on how you could architect this game in C, with the understanding that C on its own isn't equipped for creating smooth animations.

### Step 1: Set Up Your Development Environment

1. Install a C compiler (like GCC).
2. Install a graphical toolkit or library, such as SDL2 (Simple DirectMedia Layer), which provides a cross-platform API for multimedia and gaming purposes.

### Step 2: Initialize SDL

You will have to set up SDL to handle graphics. Initialize SDL with:

```c
#define SDL_MAIN_HANDLED
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO);
    // Game setup code here

    // ... your game loop ...

    SDL_Quit();
    return 0;
}
```

### Step 3: Create a Window

Use `SDL_CreateWindow` to create a window where your game will be displayed.

### Step 4: Create Sprite Sheets

Prepare sprite sheets that will contain your snake's whole level. Each sheet should have an image representation of the entire level with all positions of the snake filled in with animation frames.

### Step 5: Load Resources

Load the sprite sheets using `SDL_LoadTexture`.

```c
SDL_Texture *texture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, snakeTexture);
```

### Step 6: Implement the Game Logic

Create functions to handle game-specific logic (like movement, collision detection, etc.).

### Step 7: Animate the Snake

Use the sprite sheet by calculating the right position for each movement frame:

```c
void animateSnake(SDL_Renderer *renderer, SDL_Texture *texture, int x, int y, int anim_width, int anim_height) {
    // Calculate the correct frame on the texture
    SDL_Rect snakeImageRect;
    snakeImageRect.x = (int)((x % anim_width) * ANIMATION_TEMPORAL_FRAME_SPACE);
    snakeImageRect.y = (int)((y % anim_height) * ANIMATION_TEMPORAL_FRAME_SPACE);

    SDL_Rect destRect = { x, y, anim_width, anim_height };

    // Render the texture on the renderer
    SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, texture, NULL, &destRect);
}
```

#### Note:
This animation code assumes that you have a snake texture split into frames. `ANIMATION_TEMPORAL_FRAME_SPACE` would be a constant value that determines how much space each frame occupies on the sprite sheet.

### Step 8: Update and Render

Continuously update the game state within your game loop, particularly paying attention to the refresh rate to achieve a smooth animation:

```c
SDL_Event e;
for (;;) {
    while (SDL_PollEvent(&e)) {
        // Handle events, like keyboard input
    }

    // Update game state

    // Clear screen
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

    // Render game objects like the snake
    animateSnake(renderer, texture, snakeX, snakeY, animSpriteSheetWidth, animSpriteSheetHeight);

    // Present the rendered game output (screen)
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);

    SDL_Delay(16);  // 60 frames per second
}
```

### Step 9: Compile and Run

Compile your game with GCC, linking against the SDL library:

```shell
gcc -o snake_game snake_game.c `sdl2-config --cflags --libs`
```

### Note:
Design this carefully as using SDL with C, as with any low-level library, can quickly become complex, especially in terms of maintainability and performance optimization.

Moreover, if you find yourself repeatedly writing the same code for similar games or animations, consider learning a language with a stronger suit for such tasks, like C++, which has powerful libraries such as SFML or even game engines like Unity (which supports C# and C++, among others).

It's also worth mentioning that this guide is meant to provide a very basic overview. Developing a fully-functional snake game requires much more detail, especially in the areas of handling user input, object collision detection, scoring systems, and game state management. Remember that creating smooth and performant games, especially across multiple platforms, is a significant endeavor that goes beyond the basics outlined here.

