To generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document, you will need to use the 'tableofcontents' and 'tocloft' packages in the preamble of your document. Here is an example of how you can do this:

```latex
\documentclass[12pt]{article}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage[titletoc,titletocref]{tocbibind}
\usepackage{etoolbox}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents
\newpage
% Your content here

\end{document}
```

In this example, we first load the `tocbibind` package with the options `titletoc` and `titletocref`. The `titletoc` option enables the use of section titles in the table of contents, and the `titletocref` option allows you to use the `\cref` command to create references that will also appear in the table of contents.

Next, we use the `\tableofcontents` command to generate the table of contents. By default, this will include sections and subsections. If you also want to include chapters, you can use the following command to customize the table of contents:

```latex
\usepackage{tocloft}
\renewcommand{\cfttoctitlefont}{\bfseries}
\renewcommand{\cftchapprefix}{\textbf{Chapter}}
\renewcommand{\cftsecfont}{\normalfont}
\renewcommand{\cftsecpagefont}{\normalfont}
```

After generating the table of contents, we manually insert a new page with the `\newpage` command. This ensures that the contents appear on a separate page.

With these commands in your preamble, your LaTeX document will automatically generate a table of contents that includes sections, subsections, and chapters (if you choose to include them).

