Comparing strings in Java using the == operator is not the recommended approach, as it checks for object reference equality rather than content equality. Using == could lead to unexpected behavior and bugs, as it will only return true if the two variables point to the exact same string object in memory. To compare strings content, it is advisable to use the .equals() method which compares the character contents of both strings.

The == operator should, and must, be used when comparing primitive types (such as int, double, and short) or references of the same object. For example:
```
int a = 5;
int b = 5;
if (a == b) {
    System.out.println("a and b have the same value.");
}
```
This will print because the values are the same. 

In contrast, if we were comparing string objects, using == would not yield the desired result:
```
String a = "5";
String b = new String("5");
if (a == b) {
    System.out.println("a and b are the same object");
}
```
This statement would not print, even though both Strings contain the same character sequence.

When comparing strings, .equals() must be used instead, as it considers the content of the strings:
```
String a = "5";
String b = new String("5");
if (a.equals(b)) {
    System.out.println("a and b contain the same text.");
}
```
This will print, showing that the .equals() comparison takes into account the content of the strings.

You can also use .compareTo() method with strings, which will compare the content and return 0 if both strings are equal. However, .equals() is generally the preferred method for comparing string content, as it is more intuitive and better suited for such comparisons.

Below is a Java solution that checks if a given integer `n` is a power of three without using loops or recursion. It efficiently handles the constraints and the edge cases.

```java
public class PowerOfThreeCheck {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Test cases
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));  // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(1));  // true (1 is technically a power of three, 3^0)
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(243)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(8192)); // false
    }

    /**
     * Checks if the given integer n is a power of three.
     *
     * @param n The input integer to check.
     * @return true if n is a power of three; false otherwise.
     */
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }

        // 2^32 is the bit-length of a positive 32-bit signed integer
        // hence, 3^19 is one less than the smallest 32-bit signed negative integer
        // Using this knowledge, we efficiently check if n is one less than a power
        // of two, which implies it's a power of three.
        return (n - 1) & n == 0 && (n & (n - 1)) == n - 1;
    }
}
```

Explanation of the solution:

- If `n` is less than or equal to 0, it cannot be a power of three, so we return `false`.
- The logic `(n - 1) & n == 0 && (n & (n - 1)) == n - 1` is used to check if `n` is a power of two (minus one). In binary representation, all powers of two have exactly one bit set to 1. Therefore, `n - 1` would have all bits set to 1 but the bit at the position of the original number's one-bit, and no bits set in other positions.
- If `n` is a power of three, then `n - 1` will also be a power of two, but its binary form will not have the set bit of `n`, making `(n - 1) & n` equal to `n - 1`. Additionally, for `n` to be a power of two, all bits less than that set bit must also be zero, which makes `(n & (n - 1)) == n - 1` true. 

This approach efficiently checks if `n` is a power of three without explicitly computing powers of three, which notably avoids potential overflow and infinite recursion scenarios. It effectively utilizes bit manipulation—quite relevant when considering the constraints like avoiding loops and recursion.

